<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the National Union of Teachers (NUT)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the National Union of Teachers (NUT)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">INTRODUCTION</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2009 the National Union of Teachers (NUT) published </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">called </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Opening locked doors: educational achievement and white working class young people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The report set o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ut a series for recommendations, arising from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> two seminars held to explore the issue,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with a range of expert input</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a range of teachers, head teachers and policy experts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The full document is available on the NUT website at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><a href="http://www.teachers.org.uk/node/10792"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.teachers.org.uk/node/10792</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The project was a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">companion piece to a previous project on the achievement of young people of Caribbean heritage, as the NUT wished to reflect the fact that children and young people from working class backgrounds face many of the same issues and barriers across ethnic back</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">grounds.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2009 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">refer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">red</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to infrastructures within education which have subsequently been restructured</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, in some cases significantly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The NUT believes that the principles underpinning the recommendations remain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">relevant, however.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  A revised </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and updated version</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of those recommendations is therefore provided below.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">RECOMMENDATIONS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many schools and teachers are already working effectively to raise the achievement of white working class pupils.  The aim </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> spread best practice, encourage policymaking and leadership practices for schools which allow teachers to innovate successfully, and to address the issue of white working class pupil achievement in the context of local, family, school, community, and poli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cymaking dynamics.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Schools and their local communities require a positive response to address issues of underachievement, rather than one based on blame and recrimination.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.59pt; padding-left:21.41pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The recommendations which follow are framed in the following context.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Adopting a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">one-size-fits-all solution is not the right way forward.  Instead policy makers should proceed on the principle of building solutions for local contexts.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Aspects of the lives and experiences of working class pupils which occur outside of schools should be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> incorporated into the school curriculum.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Awareness of local dynamics, the economics of the area, family structure and caring responsibilities of pupils, the relevance of role models and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">future prospects, and other factors that may inform the outlook of w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">hite working class pupils and their families should be incorporated into pedagogy and the curriculum.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Underachievement should be seen not as endemic failure but as requiring a positive and committed response.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Teachers and schools should be provided with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the necessary autonomy to meet pupils’ individual needs.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">A goal of high achievement for all pupils should be maintained.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">An appreciation of local culture and role models should be built into the educational experiences of working class pupils.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Each scho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ol’s aim should be to appoint school staff from the local community.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Openness and respect should inform relationships both within schools and within communities.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Increasing self efficacy among pupils should be a top priority.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Recognising and celebrating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> the achievements of white working class pupils and potential role models in their communities and broader society is also vital.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Best practice should be shared.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">All schools, including those in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">deprived</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> areas, should be sufficiently funded.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">stereotyping of white working class young people should be resisted as strongly as stereotyping of all people on the grounds of race and gender.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">  It is essential to recognise that stereotypes working class girls and boys are harmful and limiting, and that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">schools should focus on assisting these groups of girls and boys to resist and subvert stereotypes about gender and class.  The NUT has published a document aimed at challenging gender </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">stereotypes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> through primary education called </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Stereotypes</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> stop you doi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">ng stuff </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">which is available at </span><a href="http://www.teachers.org.uk/files/stereotypes-stop.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.teachers.org.uk/files/stereotypes-stop.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Communication among all stakeholders and particularly among parents, school, and the community sho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">uld be a top priority.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.59pt; padding-left:21.41pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">To Government and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">its a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">gencies</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">A ring-fenced grant should be established</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, similar to the previously existing Ethnic Minority Achievement Grant (EMAG), but with a broader </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">purpose in order to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">cover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> all groups of young people in need of additional intensive support, including white working class young people, without reducing the funding available to existing groups.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The Education Maintenance Allowance (EMA) should similarly be restored in order to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> support leaners from backgrounds of social exclusion, including white working class pupils.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Post-16 entitlement funding should be restored.  Research by the NUT in 2013 demonstrated that 90 per cent of teachers in Sixth Form Colleges believed that fundin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">g cuts were having an adverse effect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> overall, and on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">disadvantaged and vulnerable young people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> in particular.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">These could include a narrowing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> the curriculum and qualifications offer available, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the discontinuation of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">enrichment activities, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">reduction or r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">emoval  of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">additional support including ‘pastoral’ and mentoring activities, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a reduction of the teacher time available per student through increase class sizes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, teachers taking on a greater number of courses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and/or reductions in staffing numbers. Seven</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ty five per cent of respondents predicted that the impact would become more significant over time by the end of the current parliament in 2015.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">A multi agency approach to tackling child poverty and supporting low income families is essential.  While schoo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">l budgets have received some protection in reviews of public sector funding, schools continue to require support from a range of other services and organisations in order to support children and young people from working class families, and their families </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">additionally require support in order to work effectively with schools and other service providers in strengthening educational opportunities and improving life chances.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Following welcome recent announcements on free school meals for infants, the Governme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">nt should outline clear plans for universal free school meals for primary school pupils in line with the recommendation from the School Food Plan by the end of the current parliament.  This will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> help support low income working parents and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ameliorate some o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">f the impacts of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> child poverty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> such as hunger and poor nutrition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">  This is a sensible way to target funding to intervene early.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Guidance for schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> on the duty to promote community cohesion should include material and approaches which valu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">e all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">communities and celebrate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> the background experiences of every child, including that of white working class pupils.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">  Schools and teachers want to learn from and enthuse each other, but in a ‘no blame’ culture.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Department for Education (DfE)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> should ensu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">re that policies and practices on tackling social exclusion explicitly factor in issues arising from social class.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Programmes for those students not in education, employment or training </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">(NEET) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">should contain an explicit focus on the needs of white working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> class young people. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The 14-19 qualifications framework should be re-examined to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ensure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> it meets the needs of children not in education, employment or training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, in particular in relation to the integration of voc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ational learning programmes which have par</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ity with ‘academic’ learning programmes within a coherent 14-19 entitlement for all learners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The curriculum and qualification offer available to them needs to be able to meet and address their needs.  The barriers to learning that some young people face c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">an be multiple and complicated and these need to be addressed before structures can be put into place to require young people to remain in education or training.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">‘Raising the Participation Age’ is a welcome development, but should not be relied upon in is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">olation as a means to reduce numbers of young people in the NEET group.  Many young people become at risk of disaffection and disengagement from learning far earlier than at the age of 16, and effective programmes for positive interventions to identify and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> address the barriers to learning which they face need to be sought if their experience post 16 is to be positive and effective, and be responsive to the circumstances of the individual.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Any review of 14-19 programmes available should reconsider the decision to move work experience, careers education and guidance, and work related learning from the National Curriculum at Key Stage 4.  Such contexts could help young people learn about and f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">or work through the school curriculum, and could assist in particular those young people who come from homes where there are is no wage earner or who come from backgrounds where they lack the social networks to learn about work or to be exposed to employme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">nt or work experience opportunities.  The NUT believes that the decision to move these functions of the curriculum to post 16 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> leaves the provision of such opportunities too late to meani</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ngfully help all young people, and that learning for and abo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ut work should form part of a continuum of learning at least from age 14.  Similarly, cuts to careers advisory services and the closure of the Connexions service have reduced opportunities for young people to receive information, advice and guidance, inclu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ding in relation to employment and careers.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Further development work with accompanying research should be commissioned on successful interventions targeted specifically at white pupils from low income backgrounds.  The purpose of this work should be to ge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">nerate and share knowledge and to promote localised solutions with systemic relevance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> should formulate specific guidance in partnership with schools with white working class pupils which encourages schools to adapt the curriculum to reflect local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> histories and developments and which provides practical examples of this work.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The National College </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">for Teaching and Leadership</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> should adopt the following approaches.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 108pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The professional development of school leaders should include school visits and exchan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ges with successful schools in working class communities, including to schools in white working class communities. Often communities may be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">simply</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> groups of residents because communities have fractured. In these circumstances the school’s efforts will be about helping to try to turn that group of residents into a community. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 108pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Such visits should be both proactive and interactive.  Potential leaders s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">hould be expected to explore with school communities the reasons for school success.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 108pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The definition of school leaders, in this context, should be redrawn to include curriculum leaders, those responsible for outward facing work with local communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, past</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">oral leaders </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">and those responsible for pupil welfare and behaviour.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">National College for Teaching and Leadership</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> should ensure that issues around white working class pupil achievement are a particular focus in Initial Teacher Training and in relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">professional development programmes.  Initial Teacher Training programmes should be reviewed in order to improve the amount of time spent on issues of equity and the way in which communities surrounding schools contribute to pupils’ bank of life experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s and skills.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">National College</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> should be given the responsibility for implementing a national programme for encouraging young people from working class communities to become teachers.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Successful schools in working class communities should be part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">national professional development strategy for all teachers.  Such schools should receive recognition and additional funding for their roles.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.59pt; padding-left:21.41pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The National Professional Qualification for Headship and Initial Teacher Training courses should give equally h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">igh priority to the impact of social class, gender and ethnicity.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.59pt; padding-left:21.41pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">High quality early years provision is crucial for providing all less advantaged groups of children with the best start in life, not only in terms of their education but also for their physi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">cal and mental wellbeing, particularly developing their self-esteem, sense of self-efficacy and future aspirations.  High quality early years education provision involves qualified specialist early years teachers working within a team of other trained prof</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">essionals to meet the learning needs of individual children, based on their different starting points.  It also involves multi-agency support, such as that which has been provided successfully by Sure Start Children Centre’s, to address any wider barriers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">to achievement, such as making relationships and working with families to ensure that every child, no matter what their background, realises their full potential.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.59pt; padding-left:21.41pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Working class families need better access to high quality early years provision.  They are l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ess likely to be able to afford to travel beyond their immediate community and are less likely to have flexible working patterns which could accommodate a journey to a setting that is not local before arriving at work.  They currently have less choice, whe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">n compared to families in more affluent areas, of ensuring that their child attends a setting which goes beyond the statutory requirements for ratios and thus improves the personal attachment between child and staff member which is so important in improvin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">g learning outcomes.  They also have less choice of whether their child attends a setting which has good access to outdoor play spaces and other educational resources, all of which can compound the difference in learning opportunities which can be provided</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> by more affluent families, when compared to those from a working class background.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.99pt; padding-left:15.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Closing the attainment gap and breaking the link family background and educational outcomes will take action well beyond the early years, however.  Recognising the inter-g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">enerational cycle of life is under-achievement and promoting interventions that operate at the earliest time in a young person’s life is just the start.  To break this cycle, an invention continuum that responds to the needs of young people throughout thei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">r passage into adulthood is needed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.99pt; padding-left:15.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The Effective Provision of Pre-School Education (EPPE) project shows that the strongest effect comes from putting good quality experiences together.  Going to a high quality early years setting plus an effective primary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> school has an enormous effect, balancing out differences by family background.  Likewise, the quality of secondary education can have a profound effect on outcomes, regardless of social background.  Narrowing the attainment gap for young people is a matte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">r of importance, both in terms of the national economic and social structure, but also for the life chances of the individual.  As stated in the latest PISA report, for example,</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">“Systems that show high performance and an equitable distribution of learning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> outcomes tend to be comprehensive, requiring teachers and schools to embrace diverse student populations through personalised educational pathways.  In contrast, school systems that assume that students have different destinations with different expectati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">ons and differentiation in terms of how they are placed in schools, classes, and grades often show less equitable outcomes without overall performance advantage.” (pg13)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.99pt; padding-left:15.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">If we are to “change the shape of the distribution of income in this country by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">eliminating the larger numbers of people who currently leave school to face, at best, a lifetime of low pay and, at worse, unemployment”, as Frank Field argued in the final report on the Independent Review on Poverty and Life Chances, then a key part of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">e national strategy for addressing the needs of white working class children must be a review of the evidence about the demographic distribution of pupils within the current school system in England and the impact of concentrating groups of disadvantaged s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">tudents in certain schools, as well as issues relating to the academic-vocational divide in secondary education.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.99pt; padding-left:15.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">To Local Authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> and the Secretary of State for Education</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Where new schools are established</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, local authorities should be required to have regard to the need for continuity and stability in all school provision and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">required also to have regard to maintaining school provision in socially and economically deprived communities.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> should be required to maintain an assumption in favour of maintaining successful 11-19 provision when considering secondary reorganisation.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Local authorities should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">be given the power and the resources to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">play a key role in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">encouraging school collaborati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ons,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> particular attention </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">:</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 108pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the continuity of curricular experience;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 108pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">pastoral support across phases;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 108pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the implications for students of behavioural expectations which might be different across different sites or phases; and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 108pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">compiling, evaluating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">and using robust evidence from their own and similar projects to inform their work.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.99pt; padding-left:15.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">To Schools</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Schools should consider whether their curricula can reflect the histories and development of their local communities.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Schools should consider what steps are n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">eeded to encourage people from all backgrounds in the local community to apply for teaching and support staff posts.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Schools should examine whether professional development for school staff can include a focus on white working class pupil achievement.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.99pt; padding-left:15.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">To</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> School Governing Bodies</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">School governing bodies should encourage co-options which are representative of the communities they serve.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:25.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Governors should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">undertake training on the relationship of social class to educational achievement.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">CONCLUSION</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.99pt; padding-left:15.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Action </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">to improve white working class pupil achievement is vital</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> but must be multifaceted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.  Failing to address the issue appropriately and effectively can fuel racism and prejudice and undermine local communities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.99pt; padding-left:15.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">This Inquiry should consider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> how communities in socially and economically deprived areas can be supported and stability secured</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> through a co-ordinated, multi agency approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Such an approach should be predicated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> on the idea that the school is at the centre of the community; fosteri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ng not only educational achievement, but contributing to social and economic regeneration.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.99pt; padding-left:15.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">For deprived communities, and children in low income families, instability and discontinuity carries the greatest risk.  Coalition policies in relation to school pl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ace planning and school type is leading to the closure of good schools, pressure on places and poor forward planning.  This poses unacceptably high risks to working class children.  Free schools, for example, are having a negative impact on social cohesion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and are leading to less inclusive schools, as has been identified in the NUT document </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Free Schools – free for all? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">(</span><a href="http://www.teachers.org.uk/files/free-schools-16pp-a4-8963_0.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.teachers.org.uk/files/free-schools-16pp-a4-8963_0.</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; text-decoration:underline">pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.99pt; padding-left:15.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The NUT believes profoundly that the principle of a good local school for every child and for every community should apply across the education system.  Nowhere is this principle more relevant than in areas of social and economic deprivation and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">for communities under challenge and pressure, such as white working class communities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>